The second scene of the canto begins with the mutual
pleasure and confusion of the two groups that play the major roles in
it, the crowd of pilgrims and the two travelers, both less (in Virgil's
case) and more than saved souls, since Dante is destined to return and
will then be a uniquely experienced penitent.
