These are Virgil's last words in the canto.  In fact he nearly
disappears from the scene once Dante and Casella take over center
stage.  He will be mentioned as forming part of the group of those who
are rapt by Casella's song (verse 115) and as departing in haste with
Dante in the canto's final verse (133).  In both cases he is behaving
less like a guide than like a lost soul.  In a sense, this is the
protagonist's first solo flight in the ^Commedia~, a moment in which he
is potentially in command of the situation.  His success is hardly
dazzling.
